 i. Mindfulness: Clients develop non-judgmental awareness of their thoughts, emotions, and bodily sensations, promoting self-observation and emotional regulation.
ii. Distress tolerance: Clients learn techniques to cope with emotional distress without resorting to maladaptive behaviors (e.g., self-harm, substance abuse).
iii. Interpersonal effectiveness: Clients enhance their communication and assertiveness skills to develop and maintain fulfilling relationships.
iv. Emotion regulation: Clients learn to identify, understand, and modulate their emotions, reducing vulnerability to emotional dysregulation.
v. Skills generalization: Therapists support clients in applying learned DBT skills to real-life situations, facilitating long-term behavior change.